# Start Ticket Workflow

## When to Use

Invoke this rule when starting work on a new ticket, issue, or feature request.

## Steps

### 1. Understand the Ticket

- Read the ticket/issue description thoroughly
- Identify acceptance criteria and requirements
- Note any dependencies or blockers
- Ask clarifying questions if requirements are ambiguous

### 2. Create a Feature Branch

```bash
# Ensure you're on the latest main branch
git checkout main
git pull origin main

# Create a new branch with a descriptive name
git checkout -b feature/<ticket-id>-<short-description>
# Example: git checkout -b feature/PROJ-123-add-user-authentication
```

### Branch Naming Convention

- `feature/<ticket-id>-<description>` - New features
- `fix/<ticket-id>-<description>` - Bug fixes
- `refactor/<ticket-id>-<description>` - Code refactoring
- `docs/<ticket-id>-<description>` - Documentation updates

### 3. Plan the Implementation

Before writing code:
- Identify which files need to be created or modified
- Consider the component structure
- Plan the data flow
- Identify reusable components or hooks
- Consider edge cases and error handling

### 4. Set Up the Development Environment

```bash
# Install dependencies if needed
npm install

# Start the development server
npm run dev
```

### 5. Implementation Checklist

- [ ] Follow existing code patterns and conventions
- [ ] Use TypeScript with strict typing
- [ ] Add proper error handling
- [ ] Ensure accessibility (ARIA labels, keyboard navigation)
- [ ] Make it responsive
- [ ] Write tests for new functionality
- [ ] Update documentation if needed

### 6. Commit Strategy

- Make small, focused commits
- Write clear commit messages
- Reference the ticket ID in commits

```bash
git commit -m "feat(PROJ-123): add login form component"
```
